{"id":"2207.06018","submitter":"Weiqiang Chen","authors":"Wei Qiang Chen, Majid Sedighi, Andrey P Jivkov","title":"Thermal diffusion of ionic species in charged nanochannels","comments":"32 pages, 9 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1039/D2NR05504J","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Diffusion of ions due to temperature gradients (known as thermal diffusion)\nin charged nanochannels is of interest in several engineering fields, including\nenergy recovery and environmental protection. This paper presents a fundamental\ninvestigation of the thermal diffusion of sodium chloride in charged silica\nnanochannels performed by molecular dynamics (MD). The results reveal the\neffects of nanoconfinement and surface charges on the sign and magnitude of the\nSoret coefficient. It is shown that the sign and magnitude of the Soret\ncoefficient are controlled by the structural modifications of the interfacial\nsolutions. These modifications include the ionic solvation and hydrogen bond\nstructure induced by the nanoconfinement and surface charges. The results show\nthat both nanoconfinement and surface charges can make the solutions more\nthermophilic. Furthermore, the thermal diffusion of solutions in boundary\nlayers is significantly different from that of solutions in bulk fluid,\ncontributing to the overall difference between the thermal diffusivity of pore\nfluid and that associated with bulk fluid. The findings provide further\nunderstanding of thermal diffusion in nano-porous systems. The proposed MD\nsimulation methodology is applicable to a wider category of coupled heat and\nmass transfer problems in nanoscale spaces.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Jul 2022 08:04:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 5 Dec 2022 14:55:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
